videos.description:
Jason Houtsma, guitar instructor for Worship Artistry reviews the all-new Vidami Blue pedal by @Vidami.  

When learning a song on Worship Artistry or other online music platforms, taking your hands off your instrument complicates and distracts from the learning process.  Imagine pausing, slowing, jumping, and looping a video, all while keeping your hands in place on your instrument as you learn.

The Vidami Blue is a revolutionary multi-modal tool that gives you hands-free control of today’s  music education technology. Experience the freedom to learn and create at home, in the studio, or on the go. Effortlessly Loop and Slow Down songs and riffs on more than *35 compatible Online Video learning platforms.

videos.title: What I learned on Easter Sunday worship. #worshipleader #worshipteam
videos.description:
This past Sunday service, which happened to be Easter Sunday, I was in more of a support role for another worship leader.

I learned that there are ways I could better support the one who is leading. Do I have everything I need before rehearsals? Did I bring everything I need so I’m not asking the leader for them? Teamwork makes the dream work–shocker!

I also realized you worry less about how the service is going and get to engage with the team.

What are some ways you could be more helpful to your team?

#worshipleaderstilllearning

videos.title: Because Of Christ Dual Guitar Instrumental | The Belonging Co
videos.description:
In this video, Nick and Jason get together and created an instrumental version of, Because Of Christ by The Belonging Co.

Why are we doing this?  There are many different ways to utilize an instrumental such as this, but a few ways to do so would be; during a prayer time, or the prayer right before the last song leading into the full version of Because Of Christ (If you have a prayer before the last song), communion would be a great opportunity to play an instrumental like this too.  It also could be fun to play when people are walking into wherever you worship. What we are really wanting is to try and inspire you to not feel like you can't be creative with your team, or feel like you only have to play it like the record always.  We think you and your church will be throughly pleased, maybe surprised, with what the worship team can pull together. Try and have some fun with it!  Let us know how you would use an instrumental during service.

videos.title: These chords are better.
videos.description:
So you recently started playing rhythm electric guitar, maybe you just came from acoustic? There is a time and place in a song to play the exact same voicings, but not the whole song.  Go check out the full video going over some helpful things Nick has picked up along the way.

videos.title: Worship Guitar | Play Interesting Chords
videos.description:
Nick is showing you a 1, 5, 6, 4 Chord Progression in the key of D.  Those chords are: D, A, Bm, G.  We will be going over 2 different ways to play this chord progression.

One way will demonstrate staying in a very tight spot on the fretboard and the other will be a bit all over the place.  Which way is better? There's really no way to answer that but to only say; whatever the song needs.  Whatever band members you have during a giving set will also dictate which type you play.  These triad types are referred to as "open-voiced triads" and "close-voiced triads".  We are only going over 2 different types but with these two types you can find your place in the mix very easily.

videos.title: Before You Practice...
videos.description:
Do you learn AND practice? Is there a difference?

I think that there is a difference and it took me a very long time to figure that out. I couldn’t remember anything but I practiced for a long time. I didn’t really understand that I wasn’t learning what was in front of me. I learned to play along with the song and I didn’t learn the actual song.

Once I recognized that and I started to go a bit slower in the learning process and then actually practicing, it got so much easier to remember everything for the service. And I ultimately got sooo much better at music.

And often times when I did come up against something that was harder, I’d just figure a different way to play something similar vs taking the time to learn the part.

Learning can be difficult, it takes time to master what you’re trying to learn, so practice as often as you can and I bet you’ll be able to learn to play what you want.

There is time and commitment involved, it isn’t an easy thing sometimes.

What have you been learning and practicing?

videos.title: Not Getting Any Better? | Worship Guitar
videos.description:
Pretty much all of us have been there.  We've all gone through it, or currently are going through it.  Being stuck, feeling like you're in a rut or on a plateau. It's no fun and it can be very discouraging at times.  Well, that's where Nick was, Jason noticed and came to the rescue.  Just by shifting things around, that Nick already knew, Jason was able to help him think a little different and start to string together some licks that he probably wouldn't have thought of before. This is not limiting to worship music at all, this is one way to become a well rounded player in general. 

Ever been stuck?

Check out our video on Jason Learning a riff from Nick:
https://youtu.be/Oc1wl8VDoU8

videos.title: How do you approach a solo? Like Jason or Nick? #worshipguitarskills #guitarlessons #guitar
Sound like a pro | Tips & Tricks
videos.description:
Here are some simple tips & tricks video for you.  Using the pentatonic scale you can actually do so much more than lawyer blues.  Give it a shot!  Try utilizing only a few of the notes and try to make something melodic with them.  We think you'd be surprised with what you come up with!

A big thank you to our friends, Doug Gould and Positive Grid for sending us the Spark 40.  It's a wonderful little (very powerful) practice amp.  All sounds in this video were recorded using the Spark 40 by Positive Grid.

videos.title: Stereo Vs Mono with Wet FX
videos.description:
Do you play in stereo or mono?  why or why not? When Nick went to stereo he found that his wet FX didn't sound like he wanted and they were super loud.  He had to adjust almost every effect, but ultimately it helped him get clearer amp tone and not just a bunch of wet FX, but they became "haunting" as he calls it.  LET US KNOW WHAT YOU USE!

videos.title: Add some flair to your soloing
videos.description: Playing the same notes and you're getting tired of it?  Maybe you're saying that you need to learn new scales or "new notes". I hate to break it to you, but there aren't "new notes". It's really all about how you add yourself to the music and adding some flair (style) to your playing can really elevate you to the next level.

videos.title: How To Learn Songs FAST
videos.description:
Ever sit down to learn a song? It can be frustrating sometimes at how long it takes, or you are practicing it and then Sunday rolls around and you can't remember any of what you practiced?  Been there?  We have too.  This actually really is the fastest way to start to get in the rhythm of learning, practicing, and mastering new songs.  Slow is smooth, and smooth is fast, that also applies for learning new songs, not just playing an instrument.

Money, resources, time, etc..? There are so many different things you could invest in your team, maybe option paralysis is setting in and you really don't know what to do. videos.title: Is the future of Worship Music in danger? Where we'd like to see it go
videos.description:
WE'RE BACK!  Hopefully everyone had a lovely set of holidays, but we are back and 2025 is going to be RAD!

We have so much lined up for this year, but first we wanted to start with some thoughts on where worship music may be going or where we'd at least like to see it go.  Chatted about some future gear predictions and some new gear choices for the year.  BUCKLE UP, it's gonna be awesome. Use the chapter markers to jump around in the video.

 Did you get any new gear? Are you excited for any new releases?  What do you think the future of Worship Music will/could look like? LET US KNOW BELOW!!

videos.title: Will this pedal get you kicked off your worship team?
videos.description:
We have heard it time and time again, that the dual rectifier is not the tone for worship, and we would agree that some of the tones in that amp wouldn't be great for worship.

In this video Nick dialed in a worship tone from the new Universal Audio Knuckles amp pedal.  It is modeling a 92 Mesa Boogie Dual Rec!  It does the hard rock/pop punk thing AND it does worship.  Let us know what you think!  We thought it actually sounded really great for worship and could absolutely be used!

https://www.uaudio.com/guitar-pedals/knuckles-92-dual-rec-amplifier.html?srsltid=AfmBOoq8c89NTDAdj-gCM1S1NKxFw5q16HSCeAj3IdzjCoBdhOs1vNjj

videos.title: Faith, Tone, and Hard Decisions | Featuring The Tone Shepherd
videos.description:
Jason and Nick talk with Devan Bumstead, from The Tone Shepherd.  We really love Devan and his heart, we hope you enjoy this conversation we had with him.  It's loosely based on relevance, but mainly it's about his journey with the next steps of being a Worship Pastor and what that looks like and his reasons for thinking this way.  The "schooling" that is in the title is just Devan being way more awesome than us. Enjoy!

videos.title: Quad Cortex or Ampero | Which modeler do you NEED?
videos.description:
This is not a head to head comparison of the two modelers. This is a real world "we only need a few things to get by" comparison.  Jason recently traveled with his Hotone Ampero and really loved using it.  So we figured we'd try to get a close enough sound out of the Quad Cortex and see if you really do need to spend the big bucks on that or go the more inexpensive route with the Ampero.  We thought they both sounded great and honestly if you don't need all the flexibility that the QC offers, we would say save some money and get the Ampero.  It is much more limited in what it can do, but as you hear in this video, it really keeps up.  So do you want to save some money? or no? Nick didn't, he loves having the flexibility and all the DSP power, but that's up to you.
